         <abstract>
            <p>In 1981 the Financial Accounting Standards Board issued Statement No. 52. This statement changed the accounting for the translation of foreign subsidiaries' operations, replacing the highly controversial Statement No. 8. The objective of this study is to assess the impact of reported earnings under FASB No. 52 on equity returns. If managers of multinational firms sought to protect accounting earnings even at the expense of reducing cash flow under Statement No. 8, the new Statement No. 52 may have caused changes in their operating procedures. Our first hypothesis is that if market agents believe there will be a favorable impact on cash flow as a result of the adoption of Statement No. 52 by the FASB, the reaction should be observed prior to the earnings announcement. We examine 11 "FASB announcement dates" to test this hypothesis. No sustained price reaction is observed. The principal hypothesis we test is that at the time of the earnings announcement, market agents will not react to that portion of the change in earnings which results solely from the switch from Statement No. 8 to Statement No. 52. Our empirical results support this hypothesis.</p>
         </abstract>
